    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-07T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-07T13:00:00-05:00" n="914"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d914">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/2754.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">American Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-07T13:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 7, 1912—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>It is possible that in case of a sudden emergency the patrol along the border may
                    be strengthened; the Army has been notified to be prepared for border patrol
                    duty. But these are only precautionary steps, and the President’s attitude is
                    identical with his attitude as expressed in his message to Congress last
                    year.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
